  "summary": {
    "as": "Introduced in Senate",
    "asOf": "2007-07-30",
    "date": "2007-10-09T21:54:28Z",
    "text": "Military Family and Medical Leave Act - Amends the Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993 to entitle an eligible employee to up to 26 workweeks of leave during a 12-month period to care for a covered service member who is the employee's spouse, son, daughter, or parent.\n\nDefines covered service member as a member of the U.S. Armed Forces, including a member of the National Guard or a Reserve, who is undergoing medical treatment, recuperation, or therapy, or is otherwise in medical hold or medical holdover status, for a serious injury or illness.\n\nDeclares that nothing in this Act shall be construed to limit the availability of such leave during any other 12-month period.\n\nProvides for the substitution of accrued paid vacation, personal, or family leave for any part of the 26-week period. Limits a husband and wife both working for the same employer to such 26 weeks altogether during a single 12-month period."
  },
